<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 92 / Manufacturers in dark mood after false dawns: From cars to
carpets, there are few signs of recovery on the horizon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Industrial Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANUFACTURERS had a bad year in 1991, and they are braced for little better
in 1992.
Companies from a range of manufacturing industries expect output to be
further down on 1991 levels. Those looking forward to growth this year
expect it will come only in the second half, if at all.
Exporters expect a tougher time with slower growth abroad and increasing
competition as Far Eastern manufacturers turn to European markets to offset
sluggish domestic demand. Selling prices remain under intense pressure and
investment plans are being reviewed.
That is the gloomy message the cars, chemicals and engineering industries
will deliver in the next two days.
UK car sales were 21 per cent down last year, following a 31 per cent fall
in 1990, according to figures to be published today by the Society of Motor
Manufacturers and Traders.
Yet 1992 will be a tough year although some senior executives have spotted
the first glimmers of recovery. Car manufacturers largely offset the decline
in the UK market by boosting exports, which were 70 per cent up in the first
10 months of last year. But slower growth in continental Europe and
intensifying competition from Japanese manufacturers will make life harder
for exporters this year.
The chemical industry is expecting output growth of at most 2.5 per cent
this year, after a flat 1991, according to forecasts to be published by the
Chemical Industries Association tomorrow. Even this modest growth will
depend mainly on the strength of the pharmaceutical industry, which should
mask further falls in output from bulk sectors such as fertilisers and
industrial chemicals. Most worrying of all is that investment this year is
expected to be at best flat after a worse than expected 15 per cent fall
last year.
The engineering industry is in sombre mood, whether one looks at traditional
metal bashing industries or high-tech aerospace companies which are facing
cuts in defence spending. The Engineering Employers Federation says
engineering output continued to fall in the last three months of last year.
It sees little reason to expect much growth this year. The EEF forecasts a
2.2 per cent increase in the fourth quarter of 1992, compared with 12 months
earlier.
There is little prospect of growth in mechanical engineering, which may have
to wait until 1993 for an upturn. The UK machine-tool industry, where sales
to some motor industry customers were down 40 per cent last year, and
construction equipment manufacturers, see no signs of improvement this year.
In electrical engineering a year-end survey by Hoare Govett, the securities
house, found that 81 per cent of companies in four main sectors of ing
products, industrial products, power equipment and rail equipment - thought
the sector was still in recession. But 62 per cent were more optimistic
about prospects than they had been three months previously. They expected UK
demand for their products to rise by 7 per cent this year after a 4 per cent
fall in 1991.
The steel industry, which is suffering fierce price competition from cheap
imports from the Continent, faces a further decline in output from 16.3m
tonnes last year to about 16m tonnes this year, according to MEPS, the
Sheffield-based steel consultancy.
The commercial vehicle industry, still suffering its sharpest post-war sales
fall, also has little cause for optimism. Its customers are not planning to
expand - more than half the 240 member companies of the Freight Transport
Association expect their fleet sizes to remain at 1991 levels.
Registrations of trucks, vans and buses were down 30 per cent last year to
about 190,000 after a 22 per cent fall in 1990.
Exports, provided by large one-off contracts with Africa and the Middle East
for some truck makers such as ERF and AWD, were buoyant. But that did not
prevent truck, van and bus production falling to 172,577 in the first 10
months of last year, nearly 27 per cent below the comparable 1990 period and
nearly 40 per cent below 1989. Most makers of trucks of more than 3.5 tonnes
expect a small rise in sales next year to about 35,000, but warn that this
will depend on whether a recovery takes hold in the first half of the year.
The textile industry starts 1992 with only a glimmer of hope for recovery,
after production fell 6 per cent last year, according to the British Textile
Confederation. Sales were down 3 per cent.
Even though textiles usually recover early in the economic cycle,
particularly low-cost items such as lingerie, hopes that this autumn
heralded an upturn have been dashed.
Sales of high-priced items such as suits and coats remain depressed. The
carpet market is also unlikely to show any sign of recovery until the
housing market recovers.
The construction industry is resigned to further decline this year. The only
good news is that the decline will be slower than in 1991.
The National Economic Development Council's construction sector group
forecasts a lean year in 1992, with output likely to be about 5 per cent
down this year after a 9.5 per cent decline in 1991.
Industry spent most of last year apprehensively scanning the horizon for
signs of recovery only to be rewarded with several false dawns. It is
approaching this year in a mood of such sombre resignation that it will take
a lot more than a glimmer of light on the horizon to lift its spirits.
By Charles Leadbeater, Andrew Baxter, John Griffiths and Daniel Green.
