<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 92 / North Korea takes steps to ease nuclear tension
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NORTH Korea yesterday told the International Atomic Energy Agency that it
would sign a nuclear safeguards agreement this month, clearing the way for a
significant reduction in tension on the Korean peninsula.
Signature of the safeguards accord would involve opening nuclear facilities
to inspection by IAEA experts.
Earlier yesterday, demands for international inspections had been repeated
in Seoul by US President George Bush, who said the US and South Korea would
call off annual military exercises if Pyongyang took positive steps on the
issue.
Mr Bush, on the third leg of an Asia-Pacific tour which will end in Japan,
where he arrives today, also emphasised the endurance of the US security
commitment to South Korea and the Asia Pacific region.
A statement from the IAEA in Vienna said Mr Chon In-chan, North Korea's
ambassador to Austria, 'today informed the director general of the IAEA that
his government will sign the Safeguards Agreement . . . pursuant to its
obligation under the Non-Proliferation Treaty.'
He said the agreement would be signed before the end of January and that
early ratification of the agreement would follow.
South Korea and the US believe North Korea is developing nuclear weapons.
This is denied by Pyongyang. Belief that a nuclear bomb could be built at a
plant at Yongbyon, 100km north of Pyongyang, within two years - far sooner
than was previously thought possible - has made the issue a top priority for
the western governments in recent months.
South and North Korea last month signed a pact of reconciliation and
non-aggression after 40 years of Cold War hostility. Seoul wanted the
nuclear issue settled before both prime ministers meet in Pyongyang next
month to sign a treaty banning nuclear weapons from the peninsula.
The US has withdrawn all battlefield nuclear weapons from South Korea, but
has said it will not withdraw some of the 40,000 US troops stationed there
until North Korea ratifies the IAEA pact.
Mr Bush reaffirmed his administration's commitment to the security of South
Korea. He congratulated Mr Roh Tae Woo, the South Korean president, for the
progress which has been made in easing tensions with Pyongyang.
He said that while the emerging post-cold war era presented an opportunity
for the US to restructure its defences, such as the closure of US bases in
the Philippines, the US would remain 'a visible, credible security presence
in the Asia Pacific region'.
President George Bush yesterday called on South Korea to remove all
non-tariff barriers to trade and liberalise its financial system, saying
that doing business in Korea is still more difficult than it should be, John
Ridding writes.
Trade liberalisation has been a principal objective of Mr Bush's
Asia-Pacific tour.
He said Korea had made 'great progress in removing visible trade barriers
over the last five years.' However there were still 'fundamental problems
that stifle the ability of foreign firms to compete in Korea.'
Mr Bush cited 'cumbersome customs procedures' and 'unjustified standards and
regulations' as some of the difficulties facing US exporters.
He also urged Korea's co-operation in the Uruguay Round of world trade
talks. Korea's refusal to allow rice imports has been one of the obstacles
to a successful conclusion of the negotiations.
Anti-riot police stopped farmers from marching to parliament to protest at
US pressure to open rice markets. The scattered protests were among several
by students, farmers and dissidents demanding that Washington end pressure
on Seoul to improve trade.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
