FT  07 JAN 92 / EC says Russia must take UK beef
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA will have to accept British beef as part of European Community aid if
emergency food deliveries are to continue as planned, European Commission
officials said yesterday, writes our foreign staff.
One official said Russia's rejection of the free UK beef - because of fears
it might be contaminated with bovine spongiform encephalopathy or 'mad cow
disease' - could have been prompted by rival EC beef producers seeking
orders from the former Soviet republics, which will get EC food credits to
pay for them.
The Commission's agriculture management committee decides tomorrow on aid
deliveries and 'it goes without saying that there will be further
consignments of British beef', a Commission official said.
Britain expressed irritation at the delays in obtaining Russian clearance
for British beef sent as part of EC aid, and a Foreign Office minister
hinted that food aid policy to Russia might have to be reconsidered.
Mrs Lynda Chalker, overseas development minister, said: 'If they are going
to react like this we have lots of other things to do, not only with our
beef but with our time.'
Brussels is concerned that Russia's initial refusal of a 120-tonne
consignment of UK beef could lead to a disastrous new consumer scare over
meat safety. The British beef came from intervention stockpiles, financed by
the EC to keep meat prices up, and last night had arrived in Murmansk, where
it was to be canned.
Editorial comment, Page 16
