<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 92 / UN chief wary of big Yugoslav peace force
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations is sending 50 military observers to Yugoslavia
immediately to monitor the ceasefire, Mr Boutros Ghali, secretary-general,
said yesterday. In a report to the Security Council, he said he would not
recommend deploying a larger peace-keeping force in Croatia until he
believed Yugoslav leaders had accepted the terms of a broader peace plan.
The terms include withdrawal of the federal army from Croatia, disarming of
Croat and Serb paramilitary units, and creation of three demilitarised areas
into which peace forces would be sent.
The ceasefire forged last Friday by the UN between the army and the Serbian
and Croatian governments appeared to be holding yesterday. But, Serbs in
Krajina, the self-proclaimed republic which forms an enclave in Croatia, are
continuing to reject terms for sending a UN peace-keeping mission. Also,
leaders in the region of Slavonia, Baranja and Western Srem in eastern
Croatia said yesterday they wanted any UN force to be stationed not in their
territory but deep in territory 'controlled by Croatian paramilitary
forces'.
President Franjo Tudjman of Croatia yesterday vowed his republic would
regain control of all its territory held by the federal army and Serb
reservists. 'We will not cede one inch of territory,' he told reporters in
Zagreb, the Croatian capital.
Mr Cyrus Vance, the UN's special envoy to Yugoslavia who is now in New York,
recommended that Mr Ghali seek Security Council agreement to send observers
as soon as possible to assess the possibility of dispatching a 10,000-member
force.
'This would have an enormous psychological impact,' a western diplomat in
Belgrade said yesterday.
'It might finally stop the fighting. But then the real work - defining
post-Yugoslavia's borders - will begin.'
France said yesterday it was was ready to contribute up to 4,000 troops to
an international peace-keeping force in Yugoslavia.
Mr Pierre Joxe, defence minister, said: 'Whether it is within the framework
of the UN or within that of a European force, we are ready to send between
3,000 and 4,000 men. That would be about a quarter of the total force that
has been mentioned.'
Croat officials are concerned that the international community is making
territorial concessions to Serbia in return for peace, and at Croatia's
expense.
Mr Zdravko Tomac, Croatia's deputy prime minister, warned: 'We are prepared
to continue the war if anybody tries to take an inch of Croatian soil from
us.' A third of Croatia is occupied by the army and Serb forces.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-15993</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CAGBXACUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920107
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 92 / Shevardnadze warns Georgia faces economic catastrophe:
Former Soviet foreign minister refuses to condemn new rulers for using force
to oust President Zviad Gamsakhurdia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE FORMER Soviet foreign minister, Mr Eduard Shevardnadze, yesterday called
for national reconciliation in his native republic of Georgia which, he
said, faced catastrophe because its resources were exhausted and its economy
was destroyed. In an interview with the FT he offered his help to build a
democratic society on the rubble left by President Zviad Gamsakhurdia.
The man who so frequently warned of impending dictatorship in the former
Soviet Union dismissed suggestions that Georgia's new rulers were tainted by
having used force to oust an elected president, whatever his authoritarian
tendencies.
'It was not so much a violent takeover as a conflict between an
authoritarian regime and democratic forces which were supported by armed
formations,' said the former chief of Soviet diplomacy, losing no time in
trying to boost the tattered image of his southern republic.
The most famous living Georgian has been rootless since his republic
declared independence from the union he served for most of his life. While
he survived as a national politician as long as the Union survived, its
dissolution last month spelt the end for him in Moscow.
He quit Georgia and his job as republican Communist party chief in 1986,
when he became foreign minister - a post in which he helped change the face
of international relations.
One of the rebel leaders yesterday described Mr Shevardnadze, who turns 64
later this month, as an able figure who could help build democracy in
Georgia. He warned, however, that he could not say how people would react to
the return of a man who once embodied Communist dictatorship over Georgia;
Mr Shevardnadze once had Mr Gamsakhurdia jailed for dissent.
However, Georgians know that Mr Shevardnadze - with his competence and
international authority - could bring them the one prize which eluded Mr
Gamsakhurdia: recognition and respectability as an independent state.
Saying that Georgia had 'a lot to do to obtain recognition and join
all-European processes', Mr Shevardnadze also predicted the republic would
soon join the Commonwealth of Independent States spurned by Mr Gamsakhurdia.
The former foreign minister praised Mr Tengiz Sigua, the civilian figurehead
for the rebel movement who has been appointed caretaker prime minister.
FORMER US president Jimmy Carter and former Soviet foreign minister Eduard
Shevardnadze will convene a summit of elder statesmen next week to seek an
end to civil conflicts in Africa, Asia and the Middle East, Reuter reports
from Atlanta, Georgia.
The 12 leaders of the private International Negotiation Network which Mr
Carter chairs will meet for the first time at his presidential library.
</TEXT>
