<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 92 / Palestinian expulsions condemned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL was strongly con-demned last night by the United Nations Security
Council, with the full backing of the US, over its decision to deport 12
Palestinian activists from the occupied territories.
The resolution, backed by all 15 council members, could pave the way for a
resumption of the US-sponsored Middle East peace talks, which had been due
to resume in Washington today. Arab delegations had delayed their arrival to
await the outcome of UN deliberations.
There were indications that Israel saw the UN condemnation of the planned
expulsions as the price it must pay for the resumption of talks.
Mr Yossi Ben Aharon, the senior Israeli negotiator who arrived in Washington
with his team yesterday, said before the vote: 'We have heard from (the
Arabs) they expect some kind of denunciation measure from the Security
Council, and that will be their admission Continued on Page 18
ticket to the talks. It's a pity they are using these tactics.'
As the Security Council prepared to vote, a Palestine Liberation
Organisation official said that the Arab delegations, including the
Palestinians from the occupied territories, would leave for Washington as
soon as the resolution was announced. It requests Israel, as the occupying
power, to ensure the safe and immediate return of deportees. It also
reaffirms the applicability of the Fourth Geneva Convention on the treatment
of civilians to the Palestinian territories occupied by Israel since the
1967 Middle East war.
The council also decided to keep the matter under review, leaving the door
open for further action once the expulsions had occurred.
Israel is considered unlikely to halt the deportations as it has already
rebuffed similar requests by the US.
The latest expulsion orders were retaliation for the killing of a Jewish
settler in the Gaza Strip. Mr Yitzhak Shamir, the Israeli prime minister,
has defended the expulsions as vital to combat terrorism.
</TEXT>
