<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 92 / Barclay brothers buy The European
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE European newspaper, founded by the late Mr Robert Maxwell, one of
Britain's most effective self-publicists, has been sold to the Barclay
brothers, two of the country's most publicity-shy businessmen.
Mr David and Mr Frederick Barclay, the 58-year-old identical twins who own
ships and hotels, yesterday announced the acquisition of their first
newspaper. It is the first significant part of the collapsed Maxwell empire
to be sold by the administrators.
Mr Alan Chamberlain, a director of the brothers' main company, Ellerman
Investments, and the new managing director of The European, said: 'I think
it's a question of timing. It's 1992 and this is an extremely exciting
period for Europe and an exciting period for The European.'
The Barclays' interests range from the Gotaas-Larsen bulk shipping line to
the Howard Hotel in London and the Mirabeau Hotel in Monte Carlo.
In the latest edition of the Sunday Times Book of the Rich, the brothers
rank merely as Super-Rich - taking 18th position with a joint fortune of
Pounds 450m. The edition, published in November, places them a full 10
places behind Mr Maxwell, who was rated as a billionaire worth Pounds 1.2bn.
The brothers are admirers of the weekly newspaper, now selling about 200,000
copies an issue. They were impressed by the commitment of the staff who
produced an issue without pay during the search for a buyer.
They admired Mr Maxwell's vision of a pan-European newspaper and also saw
its acquisition as a good business opportunity. Mr Maxwell invested at least
Pounds 50m in the venture. It is likely that the Barclays paid less than
Pounds 5m and possibly considerably less.
Mr Charles Garside, the new editor of the paper is at present the only
employee. The Barclays' purchase involved the title and equipment, but it is
not yet clear how many journalists will be hired.
The new newspaper owners began their business lives as estate agents, moved
into property, survived the crash of 1973-74 and have in the past owned
breweries.
They evidently plan serious investment in the future of The European. The
aim will be to make the paper more European and less a publication looking
into Europe through British eyes.
This may involve opening a Brussels office and distribution in Scandinavia
and Japan.
Acclaim Entertainment of the US has bought assets from Mirrorsoft, a Maxwell
producer of entertainment software for an undisclosed price.
</TEXT>
