<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 92 / UK Company News: Bunzl pulls out of food distribution in the
US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUNZL, the packaging distributor, plastics and cigarette filter company,
yesterday completed the closure of its Californian food distribution
activity, a further step in reversing the group's ambitious expansion in the
1980s.
The closure of Collins Foodservice and Corsaro Produce, which will eliminate
losses of about Dollars 500,000 (Pounds 275,000) a month, is the most
significant step taken by Mr Anthony Habgood since he became chief executive
in August 1991.
Mr Habgood said yesterday 'It was my decision to shut them down if there
were no buyers by the end of November.'
The group acquired the businesses in May 1987, paying a total of Dollars
40m, but will realise less than 20 per cent of that in shutting them:
Dollars 4m from stock and fixed assets and several million dollars from
outstanding trade debts.
Within three years combined turnover had fallen by more than 20 per cent to
Dollars 241m in 1990 producing losses of Dollars 7m. In the year before they
were acquired they made pre-tax profits of Dollars 6m on turnover of about
Dollars 300m and had net assets of Dollars 20.5m.
Bunzl said that a full provision for the food losses had been made in the
1990 annual accounts and in the interims to end-June 1991. It did not expect
the exit to generate further costs.
The move into food distribution was one of several unsuccessful strategies
in the past five years initiated by the previous chief executive Mr James
White, who left in November 1990.
Following its success in building a US network in paper distribution in the
mid 1980s, and anticipating the maturity of that business, the group
attempted to build US distribution networks in food, building products and
electrical products.
However, paper distribution has continued to grow strongly, in contrast to
the diversifications.
Financial constraints prompted the group to sell the electricals business in
1989, just two years after acquisition, although it realised a profit.
Building products have been hit by the severe US housing and construction
recession.
Mr Habgood said: 'I'll certainly wait for much better economic conditions to
assess the building products potential, and unlike the food companies, while
they are not making money they are not bleeding.'
</TEXT>
