<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 92 / Factory pay down as productivity rises: Optimism from CBI
contrasts with printing industry forecast of 'double-dip' recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANUFACTURERS are reporting a sharp increase in productivity and a downturn
in pay settlements for the second half of 1991, a trend which is expected to
be accentuated this year, according to the Confederation of British
Industry.
The CBI's findings will be welcomed by ministers as further evidence that
the recession is bringing wage inflation under control.
However, the CBI's optimism contrasts sharply with a report from the British
Printing Industries Federation which says the results of its latest trends
survey are 'frightening' and show the printing industry heading for a
'double-dip recession'.
The CBI's Pay Databank, which has in the past produced productivity
statistics more optimistic than the official data, says manufacturers which
made pay awards in the third quarter of 1991 reported annual productivity
gains of 5.5 per cent, compared with 3.4 per cent in the previous two
quarters.
According to the labour market statistics published by the Department of
Employment last month the increase in manufacturing output per head in the
third quarter of 1991 was only 1.7 per cent higher than in the same period a
year earlier.
In the current year the CBI expects manufacturing productivity to rise 6.4
per cent. Economists say some increase in productivity is to be expected
while the economy is pulling out of a recession as output starts to recover
while companies are still shedding labour.
On pay, the CBI notes a continuing decline in average settlements in
manufacturing. The third-quarter figure averaged 5.4 per cent compared with
an average of 6.3 per cent in the previous quarter and 8.8 per cent a year
before. Settlements in service companies averaged 6.4 per cent in the second
half of 1991 compared with 7.1 per cent in the first half of 1991 and 8.9
per cent in the second half of 1990.
Sir John Banham, CBI director-general, said: 'With productivity in UK
manufacturing industry rising, and pay settlements now below the level of
those in Germany and closing on those in France, the outlook for the
competitiveness of British businesses, for inflation, and  - in the longer
term for interest rates  - is good.'
The British Printing Industries Federation survey was markedly more
depressed about the economic outlook. The BPIF said that 'the small light at
the end of the tunnel seems to have been extinguished'.
The trends survey found that 89 per cent of companies had order books below
the seasonal norm at Christmas and only 7 per cent of companies believe that
conditions will ease in the first quarter of 1992. Seventy per cent believe
that trading will stay at the present depressed levels and 23 per cent see a
further decline.
Mr Nick Winks, chairman of the federation's government and industry
committee, said of the survey: 'The results are very frightening. The
printing industry . . . is clearly facing a double-dip recession.'
About 80 per cent of larger print companies and 20 per cent of smaller ones
have reduced employment and many plan to do so again in the opening months
of 1992, says the federation.
Performance pay, Page 6
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
