<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 92 / Hyundai chief moves into politics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE FOUNDER of Hyundai, the leading South Korean industrial group, has
announced that he is to retire from business and form a new political party
to oppose the government.
The decision by Mr Chung Ju Yung, one of the country's leading
industrialists, will widen a developing rift in the traditionally close
relationship between government and the big conglomerates at the heart of
the Korean economy.
The move follows Mr Chung's announcement on Friday that he was retiring from
business after a career in which he transformed Hyundai from a small
construction company into a conglomerate with annual sales of Dollars 40bn.
His political ambitions will add to the problems facing the ruling
Democratic Liberal party as it prepares for a series of important elections
this year, culminating in a presidential poll.
An official at Hyundai, Korea's largest car manufacturer and biggest
shipbuilder, said Mr Chung was aiming to field candidates in parliamentary
elections due by early May. Mr Chung would also offer his support to a
candidate for presidential elections due by the end of the year, the
official said.
His plans are the latest development in the increasingly tense relationship
between the government and the industrial conglomerates which dominate the
economy. Hyundai, which Mr Chung founded in 1947, is now involved in
electronics, petrochemicals and financial services as well as cars and
shipbuilding.
A party formed by Mr Chung would face the difficult task of overcoming
growing public resentment towards big business. Its initial objective would
be to win a minimum of 20 of the 299 seats in the national assembly.
But a party headed by the charismatic business leader would be a thorn in
the side of the DLP. The ruling party, which holds two-thirds of the seats
in the national assembly, has seen its popularity eroded by a host of
economic problems, ranging from double digit inflation to a rapidly
expanding trade deficit. It is also threatened by increased friction between
the three factions in the party.
Mr Chung, a vocal critic of government economic policies, has clashed with
the administration of President Roh Tae Woo on several occasions. In
September, Mr Chung, members of his family, and subsidiaries of the Hyundai
group were levied penalty taxes of won 136.1bn (USDollars 181.5m) for
evasion of inheritance taxes and irregular share transactions.
Details of Mr Chung's political ambitions and policies are expected to be
announced later this month.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
