<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Howard seeks better EC-wide job
notification
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT will seek to improve the system for notifying job vacancies
on an EC-wide basis during the UK's presidency of the Community in the
second half of this year.
Mr Michael Howard, employment secretary, will also use the UK's six-month
presidency to review services offered by public employment agencies
throughout the EC.
Progress on health and safety and the free movement of workers are are also
likely to be among the priorities for the government during the UK's
presidency.
The government hopes to use the presidency to persuade ministers from other
EC governments of the validity of its employment policies.
The government is keen to make clear the importance it attaches to social
affairs following the UK's refusal to accept an extension of EC power in the
employment field at the Maastricht summit in December. Social affairs has
been chosen for one of only seven informal ministerial meetings planned for
the presidency.
In spite of some suggestions that the Maastricht decisions could embarrass
the UK during its presidency, officials now seem to expect less difficulty
from that than from the continuing disagreements about the proposed
Community directive on a 48-hour ceiling for the working week.
On health and safety, government plans include progress on a directive about
the protection of workers in the coal and North Sea oil industries, and
progress on setting up an EC institute of occupational safety and health,
which the UK has urged should be sited in Edinburgh.
An international conference on risk assessment is planned, and that would
tie in with the European year of health and safety beginning in March.
Work to resolve social security issues relating to the movement of workers,
such as portable pensions, will also be high on the agenda. Much of what has
been proposed for the UK presidency would continue if Labour won the coming
general election.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow employment secretary, said yesterday that a Labour
government would create a better climate for the discussions with an early
commitment that the UK would accept the social chapter.
UK employers will not be able to opt out of the social chapter because union
negotiators will incorporate its precepts into their bargaining, according
to Mr John Edmonds, general secretary of the GMB general union.
Mr Edmonds said at a weekend conference in Oxford: 'British employees will
not put up with second-class status, and they are looking to their trade
unions to negotiate equal conditions with Europeans.'
</TEXT>
