<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 92 / Squeeze forecast for credit-card issuers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SMALLER credit-card issuers are likely to be squeezed out of the market in
the next few years, according to Barclaycard, the largest UK payment-card
issuer.
Barclaycard says the presence in the UK of 76 credit-card schemes means
there is overcapacity. Some cards will be sold to larger issuers and others
may disappear completely, it adds.
Barclaycard says that the pressure on smaller issuers was illustrated
recently by the decision of Halifax building society to increase the
interest rate on its card from 1.8 per cent a month to 1.95 per cent from
January 3.
It predicts that new entrants to the payment cards market, such as the
building societies, will issue debit cards such as Switch or the Visa Delta
card rather than credit cards.
Debit-card usage is set to grow by more than 30 per cent this year, mostly
at the expense of cash and cheques.
The more mature credit-card market is also growing, but at a slower rate.
Barclaycard forecasts that it will grow by about 5 per cent this year. It
says the credit-card market has been boosted by a recent decision by J.
Sainsbury, the food retailer, to accept credit cards.
Marks and Spencer and the John Lewis Partnership are now the only large
retailers which do not accept credit cards.
Barclaycard forecasts that large issuers will have to find additional
incentives to ensure that their customers remain loyal to them. These will
include:
purchase protection insurance cover;
Ecu-based accounts for customers who travel frequently in Europe;
improved international cash machine networks to enable cardholders to obtain
cash from virtually any machine in any country.
Barclaycard says it plans to expand its operations in the European card
market. It already issues cards in Germany, France and Spain.
It warns, however, that fraud is growing and banks will have to step up
their co-operation against fraud.
</TEXT>
