FT  06 JAN 92 / Fall in Abta membership last year was a record
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GULF war and the recession led last year to the UK's biggest annual net
loss of travel agents and tour operators, according to figures published
today by the Association of British Travel Agents.
Abta said it granted membership to 180 travel agents last year but 346 went
out of business, resulting in a net loss of 166. The most common reason for
leaving Abta was financial failure, although 77 of the travel agents were
taken over or merged with other companies.
Seventy tour operators became Abta members, but 110 went out of business,
including Mr Harry Goodman's International Leisure Group, which was then
Britain's second-largest travel company.
Abta said the rate of failures slowed during the year. In the fourth quarter
67 travel agents and 19 tour operators closed  - the lowest level since the
summer of 1990.
Abta said it expected the number of travel companies to continue to fall
this year in spite of a 20 per cent increase in demand for winter breaks and
an 8 per cent rise in summer holiday bookings.
