<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 92 / Virgin backs down on Sunday trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE battle over the sanctity of Sunday in France took a new turn at the
weekend when Virgin, the London-based leisure group, succumbed to political
pressure by deciding not to open its French stores illegally yesterday,
Alice Rawsthorn writes.
The decision by Virgin, which was fined FFr500,000 (Pounds 51,300) last week
for opening the previous Sunday, is seen as a placatory gesture to the
French government, which is preparing for a national debate on Sunday
trading restrictions.
On Wednesday, government representatives will meet trade unionists to
discuss the issue. The liberalisation of Sunday trading has long been
controversial in France because of the special role of Sunday in a Roman
Catholic culture and opposition by the unions.
One of the most powerful opponents of Virgin's Sunday trading campaign is
its chief competitor, FNAC.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
