<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 92 / Money Markets: Sterling faces test
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING will face the true test of its late rally last week, as the markets
gather in full force after the new year holiday.
Its moves in a thin market last week were dismissed as exaggerated and
misleading by many traders.
There was some speculation that the pound would come under renewed pressure,
although dealers believed that the Bank of England would be more visible in
supporting the UK currency than in recent weeks. 'The bank has sufficient
reserves to fend off a fairly good downwards push on the pound,' said Mr
David Dean, assistant chief dealer at Barclays.
The pressure for a rise in interest rates had been eased somewhat by
sterling's strength. 'At the moment things are looking comfortable,' said
one senior dealer.
Sterling, along with the dollar, had become a safe haven for investors
fleeing the D-Mark. But traders said were expecting a reappraisal of the
pound and the dollar this week.
In the US, investors will be watching the outcome of President George Bush's
visit to Tokyo this week, where it is likely that he will win some
concessions to keep the yen firm.
President Bush arrives in Tokyo on Tuesday.
The urgency of his efforts to put some life into a moribund economy will be
highlighted by the employment report due out this Friday.
'We will find out just how awful the US economy really is,' said Dr Mark
Austin, economist with Hongkong Bank.
The Federal Reserve has been debating the need for a further cut in its fund
rate as a last-ditch measure to spark economic recovery before the election.
</TEXT>
