<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 92 / Port sell-off plan faces challenge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's port privatisation programme will face a crucial test this
week when the management team which failed in its bid to buy the Tees and
Hartlepool port challenges the decision.
Mr John Hackney, who led the management-employee team, is seeking an urgent
meeting with Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the transport secretary, in a last-ditch
attempt to persuade him to reverse the decision.
If he does not, Mr Hackney said his team would seek a judicial review of the
decision taken by the Tees and Hartlepool Port Authority. Mr Rifkind has to
approve the authority's decision.
Mr Hackney said: 'We have taken legal advice and the view is that there are
certainly grounds for a judicial review.'
The management's challenge to the decision to sell the port to a consortium
led by Powell Duffryn, the engineering group, will be closely watched by
executives at other ports planning privatisation.
Three other ports - Clyde, Medway and Tilbury - have put themselves up for
sale under the 1991 Ports Act which allows the privatisation of the 114
trust ports. The challenge to the outcome of the Tees and Hartlepool sale
comes at a critical time for the three other privatisations. Potential
buyers have until the end of this week to indicate their interest in the
Clyde port. The winner of the Medway bid is expected to be announced in
early February, while the successful bidder for Tilbury is due to be decided
by late next month.
The government has already responded to criticism of the Tees and Hartlepool
decision by allowing Forth Port Authority to consider a stock market
flotation rather than a sale through competitive tendering.
The Tees and Hartlepool sale was conducted by the port authority, subject to
government approval. The authority announced just before Christmas that
Teesside Holdings, a consortium made up of Powell Duffryn, the venture
capital concern 3i and Humberside Holdings, a private company, had won with
a bid of Pounds 180m.
There were three unsuccessful bidders: Maritime Transport Services with a
Pounds 210m offer; Ocean Group with Pounds 155m; and the management-employee
team with Pounds 148m.
Mr Rifkind has said he is 'minded' to accept the authority's recommendation
and is expected to give his verdict on January 14.
Mr Hackney, chief executive of the port authority, said yesterday that the
authority contravened the sale procedure agreed with the Department of
Transport. Sales objectives outlined in the initial bid documents were not
applied at the final bid, he said. In particular, it was a stated objective
that 'all or a substantial proportion' of the privatised company should be
held by employees and management.
'We took this at face value and it reduced the size of our bid because we
had to use mainly loan finance rather than equity,' Mr Hackney said.
He said Teesside Holdings would allocate only 5 per cent to employees and
management. 'There is no way this can be described as substantial.'
</TEXT>
