<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 92 / Palestinian negotiators angered by expulsions: Israeli
action jeopardises resumption of Middle East peace talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ANGRY Palestinian leaders in the occupied territories yesterday suspended
plans to travel to Washington for next week's scheduled resumption of Middle
East peace talks in protest over Israel's decision to deport 12 Palestinian
activists.
The US was quick to condemn the Israeli action. 'We have urged Israel at the
highest levels to reconsider and rescind its decision,' said Mr Richard
Boucher, a State Department official. 'We believe deportations are a form of
retaliation and are not a remedy, nor are they a deterrent to violence.'
In Jerusalem, Mr Moshe Arens, the Israeli defence minister, said US pressure
would not persuade Israel to go back on its decision , while Mr Yitzhak
Shamir, the premier, played down criticism of the deportations. 'I think
everyone in the world understands that Israel is doing these things only
when things reach a boiling point,' he said.
In Jerusalem, a meeting of top Palestinian negotiators, led by Mr Faisal
Husseini, stopped short of breaking off the Middle East peace talks, leaving
a final decision to the exiled PLO leadership meeting last night in Tunis.
Mr Ahmed Abdul Rahman, the PLO's chief spokesman, said in Tunis the talks
could be in jeopardy unless the US and UN acted to force Israel to rescind
the deportations. But later Mr Bassam Abu Sharif, an aide to PLO leader
Yassir Arafat, said he believed the Palestinians would finally agree to
attend.
Palestinian delegates at yesterday's meeting in Jerusalem, the principal
Palestinian representatives to the talks, were less sanguine. They said
there was a growing feeling that a recent series of actions by the Israelis,
culminating in the deportations, made their continued participation in the
Mr Sari Nusseibeh, the delegation's chief strategist, said: 'The feeling was
that we can't go on with this decision in the background.' Mrs Hanan
Ashrawi, spokeswoman for the Palestinian segment of the joint
Jordanian-Palestinian team, said: 'We cannot negotiate while such conditions
prevail.'
The Palestinian delegation desperately wants some early tangible return from
the peace process - such as a freeze on further settlements - to show the
talks are worth pursuing. Two rounds of bilateral talks in Madrid and
Washington have yielded nothing, in Palestinian eyes.
US officials sought yesterday to persuade Palestinians that abandoning the
talks would play into the hands of the hardline Israeli government.
A Palestinian was killed and two Israeli soldiers were wounded in an armed
clash in the occupied West Bank yesterday. The incident came after the
bodies of three suspected Arab informers, apparently killed by Palestinian
militants, were found in the occupied territories.
</TEXT>
