<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 92 / Gold and currency reserves up Dollars 382m
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE underlying level of Britain's gold and foreign currency reserves rose by
Dollars 382m (Pounds 212.2m) last month, boosting the government's resources
to defend the pound.
The rise, which was larger than expected, takes into account proceeds of
Dollars 335m from sales to the public of BT shares, and Dollars 100m from
other countries in payments towards the costs of the Gulf war.
It is thought the Bank of England intervened modestly on currency markets in
December to support sterling, spending Dollars 50m from the reserves. More
intervention might become necessary should the pound continue its weak
showing of recent weeks.
The overall level of the reserves, which takes into account areas such as
Treasury bill transactions, rose by Dollars 211m in December, bringing the
total at the end of 1991 to Dollars 44.13bn.
</TEXT>
