<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 92 / Kenneth Grob, man at centre of scandal: Obituary
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KENNETH GROB, one of the main figures in the scandals that hit Lloyd's of
London, the insurance market, in the 1980s has died, aged 70.
Mr Grob was chairman of the Alexander Howden insurance broking group when
millions of pounds of funds were found to be missing after the group was
taken over in 1982 by Alexander &amp; Alexander, the US insurance broker.
The affair was one of the main cases that prompted a reform of the
regulatory environment at Lloyd's.
Mr Grob and his co-defendant Mr Ian Posgate, a Lloyd's underwriter, were
brought to trial in 1989 accused of siphoning off funds to private accounts
through a network of offshore companies. Mr Grob, who faced 16 charges of
theft, and Mr Posgate, were acquitted on all counts at the end of a 15-week
trial. The trial stemmed from the Pounds 150m takeover of Alexander Howden.
A post-acquisition audit revealed the shortfall in assets.
However, a report into the affair by the Department of Trade and Industry
heavily censured Mr Grob for misuse of reinsurance schemes to transfer
money.
Mr Grob was flamboyant as chairman of Alexander Howden, when he would
dispense champagne in silver goblets to visitors, in offices in Leadenhall
Street known as the 'Hanging Gardens of Howden' because of their
extravagance.
He started work in Lloyd's at the age of 16 and spent all his working life
there, except for wartime service in the RAF.
</TEXT>
